      {
        "id": 3069732,
        "name": "Robert Alfert",
        "username": "Robert.A.Jr",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/robert.a.jr/{size}/76968_2.png",
        "created_at": "2021-01-13T00:35:23.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group quote-modified\" data-post=\"4\" data-topic=\"167266\">\n<blockquote>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-post=\"2\" data-topic=\"167266\">\n<blockquote>\n<p>Hold Pegau in any case, it\u2019s a 25+ y wine.<br>\nDrink Trebbiano first.</p>\n<p>What I don t get: you HAVE to drink 2 of 3?</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>FWIW, I had dinner at a restaurant last year that had no corkage if you bought a bottle at the wine shop next-door.  Picked up a 2016 Pegau Reserve, and it was fantastic.  Totally agree that it can be held for the long-haul, but it drinks well even young.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>This.  I bought a lot of the 2017, It drinks great now but definitely able to go long.  I have some Maggies for the long haul.</p>",
